sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K392033
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: C. fermi endoglucanase CenA fused with yeast a-agglutinin Aga2 for cell surface display.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Teoh Shao Thing, Rie Takino, Kosuke Torigata
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Silver assembly of K416004 with K392006.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Assembled from Silver standard-compatible parts. Sequence shown on part's main page may not be accurate since it assumes Standard assembly. Please check sequencing results from Get This Part page instead.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This composite part consists of the Aga2 yeast surface display CDS linked to a flexible (Glycine3Ser)4 linker. It can be used by linking it upstream of the protein you wish to be displayed on the surface of the yeast cell. Note: Aga1 must be constitutively expressed by the yeast strain for Aga2 to anchor to the cellular surface.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Russell Durrett
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part comes from the Aga2 [K416000] and Linker [K416001] parts we constructed this year.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This composite part was put together following RFC23, thus the scar between parts consists of the sequence ACTAGA

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Aga2 CDS Responsible for Yeast Surface Display
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
The Aga2 protein is fused in frame with a protein that the user wants to display on the yeast cellular surface. Yeast cells constitutively expressing Aga1 (strain EBY100) secrete the Aga2 fusion protein, which associates with Aga1 through two disulfide bonds and quaternary structure to anchor Aga2 to the surface. The fused protein then is displayed on the surface of the yeast cell.
The STOP codon at the end of the CDS was removed to allow for N- and C-terminus fusions.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Russell Durrett
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This parts was biobricked from the pCTCON2 plasmid which was sent to us by Dr. D. K. Wittrup at MIT.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We removed the STOP codon to allow for N- and C-terminal fusions, which have both been proven to occur efficiently.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is a 15 amino acid flexible peptide linker protein domain that is useful for creating functional fusion proteins. The linker is to be fused in frame in between two protein domains, separating the two domains so that they each retain original functions yet will be physically connected.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Harris Kaplan
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA came from K.D. Wittrup's lab at MIT, on the pCTCON plasmid used for yeast scFv surface display.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This sequence is meant to be translated between two different protein domains, so no start or stop codon is present.
